      Ethics
   =20
 =20
To become a certified public accountant in the US, you need to pass four se=
parate exams administered by the American Institute of Certified Public Acc=
ountants, which test=C2=A0your knowledge of business, financial accounting,=
 regulation and the auditing process. The exams include multiple-choice que=
stions and simulations;=C2=A0each exam takes four hours and is administered=
 at a Prometric test center. Candidates are fingerprinted at the test cente=
r to make sure that they are who they say they are. Historical pass rates f=
or most of the exams are around 50%.=C2=A0There are also education and work=
-experience requirements before you can call yourself a CPA.Also there is a=
n ethics test? Most states require one, anyway; some don=E2=80=99t. You tak=
e that one at home on your computer or whatever. The exam used in most stat=
es is open-book and multiple-choice. Here=E2=80=99s an online CPA-study-gui=
de site:Is the CPA Ethics Exam Difficult?Not really. The exam is more like =
a self-study, open-book test. You will have plenty of time to take the test=
 and answer all of the questions. However, since the passing score is 90%, =
you have to be careful when reading and selecting the correct answer for th=
e questions.You get the idea, right? People=C2=A0spend a lot of time studyi=
ng accounting and auditing topics so that they can pass the core exams and =
become CPAs. And then=C2=A0the open-book at-home online ethics exam just so=
rt of happens. It is a minor hiccup, not the main event.=C2=A0And because i=
t is online and open-book and un-proctored and not that serious, but requir=
es a high score to pass, uh, well, this doesn=E2=80=99t seem very ethical:O=
ver multiple years, a significant number of EY audit professionals cheated =
on these exams by using answer keys and sharing them with their colleagues.=
 From 2017 to 2021, 49 EY audit professionals sent and/or received answer k=
eys to CPA ethics exams.Ahahaha sure. That=E2=80=99s from a Securities and =
Exchange Commission enforcement action fining Ernst & Young LLP $100 millio=
n for the ethics-exam=C2=A0cheating, plus some cheating on internal continu=
ing-education-type courses:The Securities and Exchange Commission today cha=
rged Ernst & Young LLP (EY) for cheating by its audit professionals on exam=
s required to obtain and maintain Certified Public Accountant (CPA) license=
s, and for withholding evidence of this misconduct from the SEC=E2=80=99s E=
nforcement Division during the Division=E2=80=99s investigation of the matt=
er. EY admits the facts underlying the SEC=E2=80=99s charges and agrees to =
pay a $100 million penalty and undertake extensive remedial measures to fix=
 the firm=E2=80=99s ethical issues.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThis action involves brea=
ches of trust by gatekeepers within the gatekeeper entrusted to audit many =
of our Nation=E2=80=99s public companies. It=E2=80=99s simply outrageous th=
at the very professionals responsible for catching cheating by clients chea=
ted on ethics exams of all things,=E2=80=9D said Gurbir S. Grewal, Director=
 of the SEC=E2=80=99s Enforcement Division. ...EY admits that, over multipl=
e years, a significant number of EY audit professionals cheated on the ethi=
cs component of CPA exams and various continuing professional education cou=
rses required to maintain CPA licenses, including ones designed to ensure t=
hat accountants can properly evaluate whether clients=E2=80=99 financial st=
atements comply with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.Great stuff. =
Look obviously=C2=A0cheating on the ethics exam=C2=A0is an incredibly dumb,=
 bash-you-in-the-face bit of irony, but there are reasons that they cheated=
 on the ethics exam and not, you know, the accounting exams. Those reasons =
are:=09It is easy to cheat on the ethics exams and hard to cheat on the acc=
ounting exams. The accounting exams are set up to detect and prevent cheati=
ng; the ethics exams are not. Why is that? One possible answer is, like, =
=E2=80=9Cyou can take the accounting exams before you have taken the ethics=
 course, so maybe you don=E2=80=99t know not to cheat, so they proctor you =
carefully, but if you take the ethics exam then you have probably studied e=
thics and you know not to cheat, so they trust you not to cheat.=E2=80=9D T=
his answer strikes me as implausible. Another possible answer is, like, =E2=
=80=9Cit is important for any professional certifying body to say that its =
members have passed an ethics exam, but you cannot teach ethics via an exam=
, so the professional bodies do not take these=C2=A0exams particularly seri=
ously and neither do the candidates.=E2=80=9D As someone who took the profe=
ssional certifying exams for law and the securities industry, I find this a=
nswer=C2=A0very=C2=A0plausible. (Prospective lawyers=C2=A0spend months stud=
ying intensively for the bar exam, which tests knowledge of law, and then l=
ike 15 minutes studying for the =E2=80=9Cprofessional responsibility=E2=80=
=9D exam, where the joke is that you can pass by always choosing the second=
-most-ethical answer.)=09Knowing accounting is very important for accountan=
ts, both in their professional self-conception and in their daily working l=
ife, but=C2=A0knowing the answers to the ethics questions=C2=A0is not that =
important. This is not quite the same as saying =E2=80=9Cknowing how to act=
 ethically is not that important in the daily life of an accountant=E2=80=
=9D (though that could also be true!), but the sort of ethics trivia that t=
he exam tests might not be that applicable to your=C2=A0everyday work. And =
when you go to parties with other accountants you probably make jokes about=
, like, LIFO or whatever, not about ethics. The thing that distinguishes yo=
u and your colleagues from other people is not some arcane ethical code; it=
=E2=80=99s knowing about accounting. If you get hired at a big accounting f=
irm and don=E2=80=99t know anything about accounting, you will quickly be f=
ound out and fired. If you get hired at a big accounting firm and don=E2=80=
=99t know anything about ethics, it=E2=80=99s possible it will just never c=
ome up.Obviously though if you are going to ask one question on an ethics e=
xam it should probably be =E2=80=9Cdid you cheat on this exam,=E2=80=9D and=
 if the answer is yes then you have definitely failed the ethics exam.I ass=
ume that after this E&Y, and the other big accounting firms, will drastical=
ly tighten up their procedures around, like, accountants emailing each othe=
r the answers for the open-book at-home multiple-choice online ethics exam.=
 Possibly that will result in their accountants knowing somewhat more about=
 the ethical code of accountancy. Still I am not convinced that the multipl=
e-choice online exam is the best way to inculcate a sense of ethics into yo=
ur workforce. So far it does not seem to work very well.
