<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Ethics</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To become a certified public accountan=
t in the US, you need to pass <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/28205671.267585/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWljcGEub3JnL3Jlc291cmNlcy90b29=
sa2l0L2NwYS1leGFt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4076bbe2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">four separate =
exams</a> administered by the American Institute of Certified Public Accoun=
tants, which test=C2=A0your knowledge of business, financial accounting, re=
gulation and the auditing process. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/28205671.267585/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2=
kvVW5pZm9ybV9DZXJ0aWZpZWRfUHVibGljX0FjY291bnRhbnRfRXhhbWluYXRpb24/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBb73fc894" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">exams include</a> multiple-choice questio=
ns and simulations;=C2=A0each exam takes four hours and is administered at =
a Prometric test center. Candidates are fingerprinted at the test center to=
 make sure that they are who they say they are. Historical pass rates for m=
ost of the exams are around 50%.=C2=A0There are also education and work-exp=
erience requirements before you can call yourself a CPA.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Also there is an ethics test? Most states require one, anyway=
; some don=E2=80=99t. You take that one at home on your computer or whateve=
r. The exam used in most states is open-book and multiple-choice. Here=E2=
=80=99s an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2820567=
1.267585/aHR0cHM6Ly9pcGFzc3RoZWNwYWV4YW0uY29tL2NwYS1ldGhpY3MtZXhhbS8/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB869cde38" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">online CPA-study-guide site</a>:</p><b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is the CPA Ethics Exam Difficult?</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not really. The exam is more like a self-stud=
y, open-book test. You will have plenty of time to take the test and answer=
 all of the questions. However, since the passing score is 90%, you have to=
 be careful when reading and selecting the correct answer for the questions=
.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You get the idea, right? Peo=
ple=C2=A0spend a lot of time studying accounting and auditing topics so tha=
t they can pass the core exams and become CPAs. And then=C2=A0the open-book=
 at-home online ethics exam just sort of happens. It is a minor hiccup, not=
 the main event.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And because it is on=
line and open-book and un-proctored and not that serious, but requires a hi=
gh score to pass, uh, well, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/28205671.267585/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluL=
zIwMjIvMzQtOTUxNjcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB81a4689c" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this doe=
sn=E2=80=99t seem very ethical</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Over multiple years, a significant number of EY audit professionals ch=
eated on these exams by using answer keys and sharing them with their colle=
agues. From 2017 to 2021, 49 EY audit professionals sent and/or received an=
swer keys to CPA ethics exams.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Ahahaha sure. That=E2=80=99s from a Securities and Exchange Commission <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28205671.267585/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0xMTQ/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB7c58ba0d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">enforcement action</a> fining Ernst &amp; Young =
LLP $100 million for the ethics-exam=C2=A0cheating, plus some cheating on i=
nternal continuing-education-type courses:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today charged Ernst &amp=
; Young LLP (EY) for cheating by its audit professionals on exams required =
to obtain and maintain Certified Public Accountant (CPA) licenses, and for =
withholding evidence of this misconduct from the SEC=E2=80=99s Enforcement =
Division during the Division=E2=80=99s investigation of the matter. EY admi=
ts the facts underlying the SEC=E2=80=99s charges and agrees to pay a $100 =
million penalty and undertake extensive remedial measures to fix the firm=
=E2=80=99s ethical issues.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CT=
his action involves breaches of trust by gatekeepers within the gatekeeper =
entrusted to audit many of our Nation=E2=80=99s public companies. It=E2=80=
=99s simply outrageous that the very professionals responsible for catching=
 cheating by clients cheated on ethics exams of all things,=E2=80=9D said G=
urbir S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Enforcement Division. ...</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">EY admits that, over multiple years, a signif=
icant number of EY audit professionals cheated on the ethics component of C=
PA exams and various continuing professional education courses required to =
maintain CPA licenses, including ones designed to ensure that accountants c=
an properly evaluate whether clients=E2=80=99 financial statements comply w=
ith Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Great stuff. Look obviously=C2=A0<em>cheating on the ethics=
 exam=C2=A0</em>is an incredibly dumb, bash-you-in-the-face bit of irony, b=
ut there are reasons that they cheated on the ethics exam and not, you know=
, the accounting exams. Those reasons are:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type:=
 decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">It is easy to cheat on the ethics exams and hard to cheat on the a=
ccounting exams. The accounting exams are set up to detect and prevent chea=
ting; the ethics exams are not. Why is that? One possible answer is, like, =
=E2=80=9Cyou can take the accounting exams before you have taken the ethics=
 course, so maybe you don=E2=80=99t know not to cheat, so they proctor you =
carefully, but if you take the ethics exam then you have probably studied e=
thics and you know not to cheat, so they trust you not to cheat.=E2=80=9D T=
his answer strikes me as implausible. Another possible answer is, like, =E2=
=80=9Cit is important for any professional certifying body to say that its =
members have passed an ethics exam, but you cannot teach ethics via an exam=
, so the professional bodies do not take these=C2=A0exams particularly seri=
ously and neither do the candidates.=E2=80=9D As someone who took the profe=
ssional certifying exams for law and the securities industry, I find this a=
nswer=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>plausible. (Prospective lawyers=C2=A0spend mo=
nths studying intensively for the bar exam, which tests knowledge of law, a=
nd then like 15 minutes studying for the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/28205671.267585/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmNiZXgub3JnL2V4YW1z=
L21wcmUv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf9b46524" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=E2=80=9Cprofessional r=
esponsibility=E2=80=9D exam</a>, where the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/28205671.267585/aHR0cHM6Ly9zY2hvbGFybHljb21tb25zLm=
xhdy53bHUuZWR1L2NnaS92aWV3Y29udGVudC5jZ2k_cmVmZXJlcj0maHR0cHNyZWRpcj0xJmFyd=
GljbGU9MTU1NCZjb250ZXh0PXdsdWxy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc8da5bc4" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
joke</a> is that you can pass by always choosing the second-most-ethical an=
swer.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Knowing accounting is very =
important for accountants, both in their professional self-conception and i=
n their daily working life, but=C2=A0<em>knowing the answers to the ethics =
questions=C2=A0</em>is not that important. This is not quite the same as sa=
ying =E2=80=9Cknowing how to act ethically is not that important in the dai=
ly life of an accountant=E2=80=9D (though that could also be true!), but th=
e sort of ethics trivia that the exam tests might not be that applicable to=
 your=C2=A0everyday work. And when you go to parties with other accountants=
 you probably make jokes about, like, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/28205671.267585/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2k=
vRklGT19hbmRfTElGT19hY2NvdW50aW5n/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe9199e22" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">LIFO</a> or whatever, not about ethics. The thing that distinguishes you =
and your colleagues from other people is not some arcane ethical code; it=
=E2=80=99s knowing about accounting. If you get hired at a big accounting f=
irm and don=E2=80=99t know anything about accounting, you will quickly be f=
ound out and fired. If you get hired at a big accounting firm and don=E2=80=
=99t know anything about ethics, it=E2=80=99s possible it will just never c=
ome up.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously though if you are g=
oing to ask one question on an ethics exam it should probably be =E2=80=9Cd=
id you cheat on this exam,=E2=80=9D and if the answer is yes then you have =
definitely failed the ethics exam.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I assume=
 that after this E&amp;Y, and the other big accounting firms, will drastica=
lly tighten up their procedures around, like, accountants emailing each oth=
er the answers for the open-book at-home multiple-choice online ethics exam=
. Possibly that will result in their accountants knowing somewhat more abou=
t the ethical code of accountancy. Still I am not convinced that the multip=
le-choice online exam is the best way to inculcate a sense of ethics into y=
our workforce. So far it does not seem to work very well.</p><table class=
